      "content": "Wait, I just ran a quick check. If N=1,000,000, a Python list of 1,000,000 integers actually takes way more than 8MB. Each integer object in Python is at least 28 bytes, and the list itself stores pointers to these objects which are 8 bytes each. So 1,000,000 entries is already like 36MB just for one list, let alone two (parent and rank). \n\nWith two lists, you're hitting 72MB minimum before you even start reading edges. The judge is going to kill it immediately.\n\nIs there a way you can trick the memory or use a different way to store this that doesn't involve standard Python lists? I really need this to pass the 64MB check.",
